        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>belt ornaments [300411649], worn costume accessories [300209274], costume accessories [300209273], costume (mode of fashion) [300178802], Costume (hierarchy name) [300209261], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Items, usually of metal, flat, and rectangular or oval in shape, worn on the belt of a uniform or other costume. When part of a military uniform, often bear insignia of rank or unit. Includes plates worn on waist belts, shoulder belts, and sword belts. Usage sometimes overlaps with "belt plaques," which may be made of various materials, although items made of stone are typically called "belt plaques" rather than "belt plates." </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000012401/Ross, Military Uniforms (1980)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Instrumento de metal, generalmente plano y de forma rectangular u oval, que por lo general sostiene insignias de rango o unidad. Incluye aquéllas que se llevan sobre cinturones de cintura, de hombros y de espadas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Metalen plaatjes, in het algemeen plat en rechthoekig of ovaal van vorm, die gewoonlijk insignes van rang of eenheid aanduiden; omvat plaatjes die worden gedragen op tailleriemen, schouderriemen en degenkoppels.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099090/Van Dale Online Woordenboek (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一般為扁平方形或橢圓形，通常帶有階級或單位佩章，包括腰帶、肩背帶，和劍帶上的金屬紋章。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
